node.text:
I posted this on my stories yesterday, and I thought it would be good to give it a more permanent space on my feed after the response I received.⁣
⁣
Unlearning toxic hustle culture can be really, really difficult. ⁣
⁣
I don’t know about you, but I grew up with people all around me glorifying working nonstop and getting little sleep. Biting off more than you can chew and also feeling exhausted were worn like badges of honor. It felt like a competition - who can feel the most like shit? 💩 ⁣
⁣
As a result, I felt an incredible amount of pressure to always do more, more, more, and I would find myself feeling overwhelming guilty any time I dared to take a bit of rest. ⁣
⁣
Can we flip the script? ⁣
⁣
Can we celebrate actually taking care of ourselves, getting adequate rest, and not running on fumes? ⁣
⁣
Honestly, I’m at my best when I sleep lots, eat ample nutritious food, and give myself regular downtime. ⁣
⁣
Looking after your mental health and prioritizing self-care can be in the “in” thing to do. 🥰

node.title: You’re not better off for suffering more

This is not how things should be. ⁣
⁣
I don’t want to be another person who’s aware of inappropriate behavior, knowing it’s wrong, and still do nothing except shake my head in disapproval and move on. ⁣
⁣
In this video, I briefly touch on some events that have transpired relating to @the_issn over the past 8 days. ⁣
⁣
In addition to sexism and fat phobia displayed by the social media pages linked through the ISSN website, the feeds have been included personal, bigoted views posted by Dr. Jose Antonio that are not reflective of ISSN alleged values. ⁣
⁣
Sincerely, I was hoping that it would not come to this. I made numerous attempts to make it clear privately to ISSN leadership over the past week that posting a diversity statement on the website was not enough. It’s felt performative; this is not true allyship. ⁣
⁣
What’s happened instead is what appears to be a quiet clean-up job. But many individuals, including members like myself and other onlookers who have been watching these events unfold, have been looking to ISSN leadership to address what’s happened head on. We want to know where you stand.⁣
⁣
“The ISSN does not discriminate on the basis of race, color, creed, religion, sex, gender expression, age, national origin/ancestry, disability, marital status, sexual orientation, or military status, in any of its activities or operations.” ⁣
⁣
Do you stand by this statement, even when it’s being violated by individuals at the top of your own organization? ⁣
⁣
None of this had to be this way. All of this could have been a near non-issue, and I would have gained tremendous respect for the ISSN had they responded to this directly and swiftly. But we’ve waited and waited with little to nothing changed.⁣
⁣
I expected more. ⁣
⁣
ISSN, your silence has been so, so loud. ⁣
⁣
And because you have been quiet, I am making noise. ⁣
⁣
Please show @amandahowellhealth your support. She has been one of the only individuals brave enough to call out  inappropriate behavior displayed by ISSN social media and has been blocked and ignored by the leaders. ⁣
⁣
#InternationalSocietyOfSportsNutrition #ISSN

Not gonna lie, I have never taken so many long pauses while filming a video (I’ve cut most of them out). This one really got me in the feels…. 😢💔⁣
⁣
As I mentioned on my stories yesterday, opening up about my eating disorder history can be pretty painful. In some ways, I at times feel as though I’m re-living the many sad moments of my teens and 20s. But I also believe that sharing my story can help others. ⁣
⁣
The purpose of this video is threefold. I want to: ⁣
⁣
✨take the shame and stigma out of eating disorder struggles. ⁣
✨shed more light on how debilitating eating disorders can be. ⁣
✨normalize admitting when you’re not okay and normalizing getting help. ⁣
⁣
I also continue to share more about what this experience was like for me and some factors that helped me get better. ⁣
⁣
NationalEatingDisorders.org ⁣
⁣
#NEDAwareness #edrecovery

In today’s video, I respond to some comments that a user made against my argument that we shouldn’t be labeling foods as “good” or “bad”, nor do we need to completely forbid nutrient-devoid foods from our diet. This individual cited a 2019 study by Murray. ⁣
⁣
This person’s argument is one that many, many try to make. I’ll show you why this argument is invalid. ⁣
⁣
This particular study aimed to quantify the impact of “suboptimal” dietary intake on non-communicable diseases mortality and morbidity. ⁣
⁣
Researchers examined numerous dietary factors, including mean daily consumption/intake of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, nuts and seeds, and more. They found that poor dietary habits at the population level was a risk factor for several health outcomes. These findings are not surprising, and I also don’t disagree with them. ⁣
⁣
In the Discussions section, they wrote, “suboptimal diet is responsible for more deaths than any other risks globally, including tobacco smoking,” but as I mention in my video, this doesn’t mean that having one donut equates to a “bad diet,” nor does it equate to being worse than smoking. ⁣
⁣
Unfortunately, this paper does not support this individual’s argument. Their mistakes include: ⁣
⁣
❌assuming that one food in isolation provides an accurate picture of the quality of overall diet ⁣
❌assuming that eating a donut means that your fruit, vegetable, legume etc. consumption is low (in reality, you can both eat a donut and still consume plenty of nutrient-dense foods throughout the day) ⁣
❌taking one statement made in a research paper and making a huge logical leap that does not work ⁣
❌resorting to appeal to authority at the end⁣
⁣
Should we be encouraging a diet high in nutrients? Absolutely. ⁣
And should we also be teaching people not to demonize foods? For sure. ⁣
Is it okay to have some nutrient-devoid foods every now and then and still have an overall high quality diet while maintaining a healthy relationship with food? You bet. ⁣
⁣
All three of these statements can be true at the same time. ⁣
⁣
One donut - or two donuts, or three donuts - does not a bad diet make. ⁣
⁣

⚠️TW: EATING DISORDER, CHRONIC ILLNESS⚠️

Earlier this week, @bdccarpenter and I sat down to further discuss the misconception that leaner does not always mean you’re healthier. Both he and I have personal experiences of this statement being the furthest thing from the truth. 

For me, I became anorexic and bulimic at the age of 14, then continued to struggle with bulimia and then only binge eating for about 8 years afterwards. 

For Benji, his Crohn’s disease saw him rapidly shedding 50lbs off his frame in a short period of time with barely enough energy to get out of bed. 

Judging by the many many messages I’ve received from my followers, I think it’s safe to say that a lot of you can relate and have had similar experiences. 

Suffice to say, we are both much healthier (not to mention happier) now with more body fat on our frames than before. 

Because yes, there is more to health than body fat and body size. 

My mental peace with food, exercise, and my body is everything now. I’ve worked hard to get back to this place where I can enjoy what and how I eat and exercise while simultaneously doing so in a way that treats my body well. 

Don’t miss the forest for the trees. ❤️

Gym Shaming & Gaslighting⁣
⁣
Bullying is not okay. ⁣
Shaming people in the gym is not okay. ⁣
⁣
It’s time we stop tolerating this kind of behavior. ⁣
⁣
I’d love to see more people standing up to and calling out individuals who do this. ⁣
⁣
When someone tells you that they find something you have said or done to be offensive or hurtful, the appropriate response is NOT to tell them they are too sensitive, need thicker skin, need to grow a backbone, or any variation thereof. ⁣
⁣
These are all examples of gaslighting, which is a form of manipulation in which you are made to question your own thoughts, emotions, and sanity. By gaslighting someone who is speaking up against bullying, you are normalizing that kind of behavior. This happens all the time. ⁣
⁣
I’m all for humor. I’ll make fun of myself more than anyone, and anyone who knows me in real life is aware of how goofy I can be. ⁣
⁣
But know when you’ve completely missed the mark. ⁣
⁣
I recently learned that in comedy, there are terms “punching up” and “punching down”. Punching up is generally preferred as the subject matter has more power. When you punch down, you attack people already marginalized and with less power. The video I talked about yesterday entailed punching down. It’s important to know the difference. ⁣
⁣
And if you think it’s okay to mock people in the gym, or arguably worse - actively defend those who do so… take a seat. You’re part of the problem. ⁣
⁣
Be kind… but take no shit. ⁣

node.text:
I like to post this reminder every few months as inevitably there is someone who has been considering shelling out $$$ for that one influencers detox diet program they’ve been pushing. 

Don’t do it. 
⁣
Detox diets are dietary interventions that purport to eliminate toxins from the body, help with fat loss, and/or improve health. Many of these diets entail extreme dietary restriction whereby you can only consume a handful of food items for days and weeks at a time. Truth to be told, I understand the allure: a simple, straightforward method that can get you quick results in a relatively short period of time - what’s not to like? ⁣
⁣
There are zero clinical studies to date demonstrating the effectiveness of commercial detox diets (to the best of my knowledge). Some foods do appear to have detoxification properties, but you can likely reap the benefits by simply adding them to your diet rather than removing everything else. A few studies have shown that detox diets can eliminate pollutants or enhance liver detox, but these studies each have small sample sizes and flawed methodologies. The fact of the matter is, the liver, kidneys, skin, lungs, and gastrointestinal system on their own do an excellent job of eliminating unwanted substances from the body. ⁣
⁣
In fact, low energy detox diets can actually increase stress, cortisol, and appetite and can increase the probability of binge eating and rebound weight gain (Mazurak et al., 2013; Pankevich et al., 2010; Tomiyama et al., 2010). So while they may be effective at eliciting short-term changes via calorie restriction - which, by the way, you do not need a detox diet for - the long-term results tend to be more grim. Additionally, detox dieting makes you more prone to nutrient deficiencies and electrolyte imbalances, and in more severe cases, hospitalization or death (Johnstone, 2007). ⁣
⁣
Also, nothing wrong with making money. But making money by pushing bullshit claims? Not cool. ⁣
⁣
Don’t confuse correlation with causation. And lastly, don’t fall for the hype! ⁣
⁣
🎵: I Miss You - Blink 182 
⁣
#DetoxDiets #EatLiftThrive

Let be me clear: knowing that you have permission to eat something is distinct from making the choice to eat it right away. 

You can understand that something is not off-limits and still make the decision to eat it tomorrow instead of today. 

Maybe you’ve already eaten enough added sugars and not enough fibrous veggies today, or it’s a stale, dry cookie that you’ve been eyeing out of boredom. Under these circumstances, it may be a better idea - for now - to pass. 

Or maybe you decide that yes, enjoying your friend’s famous chocolate chip cookie is absolutely the right decision, or perhaps you’re working to overcome your food fears, and desserts are something you’ve been most apprehensive about. Or it may simply be the case that you really, really want the cookie. 

There is not always a one-size-fits-all-in-every-circumstance correct choice.

Ultimately, the decision to eat the cookie or not is yours and yours alone. Sometimes saying “yes” is right; other times, it’s “no”. 🍪

When performing exercises from the squat rack, I generally recommend facing INTO, not out of the rack for safety reasons. 

Facing the rack allows you to more effectively re-rack the bar after your set. This is especially important if you’re extra fatigued and less likely to pay close attention to what you’re doing. 

One of my clients told me about a time from before she worked with me. After performing a heavy set of back squats with nearly 200lbs on her back while facing OUT of the rack, she missed the pin to re-rack one side of the barbell, and she tipped over completely. 😰 Thankfully she was fine, but that could have ended badly. 

(I’m demoing this with an empty bar because safety 🙃)

Face INTO, not OUT of, the rack! 👊

node.text:
Ever since I started running again 7+ months ago, I’ve received a surprising number of messages from people asking why I’m trying to lose body fat. Despite my repeating that my goal with running is performance-based (beat my mile time record of 5’55” 🏃🏻‍♀️), there is still an underlying assumption that I’m dieting. But this assumption is incorrect. 

You can exercise for reasons including: 

✅support mental health 
✅improve bone density and/or cardiovascular fitness 
✅improve cognitive abilities 
✅increase quality of life 
✅meet a performance goal 
✅increase self-esteem and confidence 

…and the list goes on! 

Let’s not automatically make the assumption that someone lifting weights at the gym or going for a run at the park is only there to change their body shape. ❤️

node.text:
I stumbled across this video today and honestly, we need more people like @thewizardlizz 👏👏👏

And she is absolutely right: sometimes all it takes is one person making an unkind remark about their body size for someone to start skipping meals and wade into eating disorder territory. 

This is serious stuff, and it’s important that we call out these kinds of inappropriate unsolicited comments. 

YES, we should work on becoming more secure with our bodies and ourselves as individuals. And ALSO, we can simultaneously stand up to those making inappropriate remarks about other people’s bodies. 

To those of you who will inevitably say that people need to “stop being so sensitive”: stop shaming people for having feelings and being human. Take accountability for harmful behavior rather than shirking responsibility and pretending like these kinds of remarks are fine.

@thewizardlizz writes:   “I’m doing it for my younger self who developed and ED cause of people like this who constantly told me what and when I should or shouldn’t eat. I am doing this for every girl/boy out there who has suffered or is still suffering from an ED, for everyone who has been put down and didn’t feel comfortable speaking up. You are worthy, you CAN and SHOULD defend yourself. My body is perfect not because I am “skinny” but because I am healthy alhamdulillah. I love my body and so should everyone. May all of you be blessed and get everything your heart desires.” 

❤️

node.text:
I frequently talk about the importance of enjoying the process to achieve your outcome goal, whatever that is. 

But that doesn’t mean that you will always be excited about doing the thing. 

You won’t be pumped about every single workout. 
You won’t necessarily want to eat the veggies. 
You may be tempted to skip the run. 

All of these feelings are normal and valid. 

And sometimes it’s still important to do the thing even when you don’t feel like it. 

That to me is what separates an amateur from someone who takes their craft seriously. 

(But of course, there are times when not doing a target behavior might make more sense for your self-care depending on circumstances.) 

And remember, you can do hard things. 👊

One of my favorite analogies that I like to share every now and then. 

This metaphor can apply to: 

✅learning a new skill 
✅working towards that degree 
✅trying to achieve a performance goal
✅building muscle or gaining strength 

and more. 

Just because you don’t notice the progress from one day to the next doesn’t mean it’s not happening. 

Keep going. ❤️

10 years ago, I was very much stuck in the diet mentality. I thought that health was all about having low body fat, and I was on a seemingly never-ending quest to diet. 

Restriction was the name of the game. 

I believed that eating anything more than 1,200 Calories was too much food, and daring to consume more made me mentally weak and undisciplined. Ironically, it was the high level of rigid restriction coupled with my all-or-nothing mentality that led me to continually self-sabotage with endless rounds of binge eating, followed by waves of guilt and shame, then even more restriction. 

My adherence was terrible, I felt like crap, and this subsequently eroded my self-confidence. 

I’M SO GLAD I KNOW BETTER NOW. 

Everyone’s calorie needs will differ depending on your activity level, body weight, goal, genetics, and more. However, it’s safe to say that 1,300 is very likely not nearly enough for you to be your healthiest, happiest self. Moreover, I have had complete peace of mind with food over the past several years, and that to me is priceless. 

Food is not the enemy. 
Rigid restriction backfires in the long run. 

What other diet rules did you used to adhere to?

I’m sure we can think of at least one person in our lives - and maybe that’s ourselves - who has, at one point or another, not felt safe or welcome at a gym or any other fitness space. Felt harassed, ogled, and overall dehumanized and objectified when we were simply going about our lives, minding our own business. I know I certainly have. 

That’s not okay. And I don’t agree it’s something we need to “just accept”. 

I want to help foster a safe space for women and everyone on my platforms. 

I’ll be the first to admit that I haven’t always done this in the past, and at times actively harmed women with my words and actions - even if that was not my intent. 

Telling women to further shrink themselves literally and metaphorically to be deemed acceptable in society, continually modifying our own behavior to avoid the harassment of others is not it. 

The internalized misogyny is deep-rooted in many of us, and to call it out and unlearn can be really uncomfortable and difficult. 

Let me make it clear that I do not support: 

further putting the onus on women to be responsible for other people’s behavior 
using “feminist, “woke”, and “social justice warrior” as insults 
calling women “too emotional” any time we call out inappropriate behavior or stand up for ourselves 
any kind of degradation of women 

There’s a lot of good that can happen when you push and push for change. 👊

I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again: on my platform, you are safe. 🥰
